  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT302-kilavi">varaiviṭaik kavaṉṟa tōḻikkuk kiḻatti colliyatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Spoken by HER to the confidante who was anxious about
          the time of marriage. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT302">
          <l> uraitticiṟ ṟōḻiyatu puraittō vaṉṟē</l>
          <l> yaruntuya ruḻattalu māṟṟā mataṉṟalaip</l>
          <l> perumpiṟi tāka lataṉiṉu mañcutu</l>
          <l> maṉṉō viṉṉu naṉmalai nāṭaṉ</l>
          <l> piriyā naṇpiṉa riruvaru meṉṉu</l>
          <l> malarataṟ kañciṉaṉ kollō palaruṭaṉ</l>
          <l> ṟuñcūr yāmat tāṉume</l>
          <l> ṉeñcat tallatu varavaṟi yōṉē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>Tell [me], friend, [is] that great? No! <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta">	atu puraittō aṉṟē </term>: the impact of the short sentence remains unclear because it is not made explicit to what the <term xml:lang="ta"> atu </term> refers here, any more than to what refers the <term xml:lang="ta"> ataṟku </term> of line 6. Is it HIS action of coming or not coming which is meant? </note> </l>
          <l>We cannot bear the heavy misery and on top of that</l>
          <l>we fear more than that the coming of the great other. <note place="foot"> Here just like in KT 69.1 <term xml:lang="ta"> perum piṟitu </term> seems to refer to dying. </note></l>
          <l>Alas! And has now the man from a good mountain land</l>
          <l>become afraid,<note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> añciṉaṉ </term>: the perfective aspect probably expresses the aorist of a concrete situation. </note> because of that, gossip,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">which says “the two of them [are] of inseparable friendship”?</l>
          <l rend="indent2">At midnight too, into the village where many sleep together,</l>
          <l>he knows nothing of coming, except into my heart.</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
